Kubernetes is made up of there is control plane which is like the master node & worker node.so its a cl8 master made up of the master node & worker node
 the master node has components including the Api server which is the main administrattive point into the cl8, any REQ made into the cl8, the REQ is managed
by the Api server 
we also have the scheduler incharge of scheduling pods on nodes & it schedules pods base on how much resources the nodes are having
we aslo have the controller managers & their function is to ensure that the state of resources that k8 is creating is maintained for eg if we need 10 pods
the ccontroller manager will ensure that we have 10 pods running at all times.
we have the ETC, which is a key value store that stores & captures all info or all REQ made in the cl8, 
those are the components of the master node

Also we have the worker node which is made up of the pry node agent which is kubelet, we also have the netwrk agent which is kube proxy & very importantly
we have the container runtime, since k8 manages & ochestrates containers the container runtime is in charge of creating & starting the container & in this case
in our env we are basically using container D as our conatiner runtime 
its also worth noting here that in the k8 arachitecture for any task to be executed in the cl8 a rEQ has to made & the REQ in k8 is called an Api call & for 
the REQ to be made, we need what is called the kubectl which is the command line utility for k8 or a dashboard, k8 dashboard, so either kubectl or a k8
dashboard is able to make the REQ into the cl8 & whatever REQ is made the REQ wll be processed by the APi server
and for any REQ to be made, it needs to go through authentication & authorization & in k8 we use what is called the RBAC to be able to authenticate 
however authentication happens via the kube config file, so with the help of the kube config file, users, k8 engrs are able to connect into the cl8 
and perfrom diff task howerver for task to be executed, administrators are authorized through the role base access control
